revision.text:
{{Speciesbox |image = Acacia confusa-01.jpg |status = LR/lc |status_system = IUCN2.3 | status_ref = <ref name="iucn">{{IUCN2013.2| assessor=World Conservation Monitoring Centre| year=1998| id=34744 | title=Acacia richii| downloaded=3 May 2014}}</ref> |genus = Acacia |species = confusa |authority = [[Elmer Drew Merrill|Merr.]] |range_map = Acacia-confusa-range-map.png |range_map_caption = Range of ''Acacia confusa'' |synonyms = * ''Acacia richii auct. non'' [[Asa Gray|A. Gray]] * ''Racosperma confusum'' ([[Elmer Drew Merrill|Merr.]]) [[Leslie Pedley|Pedley]]<ref>[http://www.ildis.org/LegumeWeb?sciname=Racosperma+confusum International Legume Database & Information Service (ILDIS)]</ref> |}}
'''''Acacia confusa''''' is a perennial tree native to South-East Asia. Some common names for it are '''acacia petit feuille''', '''small Philippine acacia''', '''Formosa acacia''' (Taiwan acacia) and '''Formosan koa'''. It grows to a height of 15m. The tree has become very common in many tropical Pacific areas, including Hawaii, where the species is considered invasive.<ref>[http://www.hear.org/Pier/wra/pacific/acacia_confusa_htmlwra.htm Pacific Island Ecosystems at Risk (PIER)]</ref>
==Uses== Its uses include chemical products, environmental management and food and drink. The bark may be ground into a powder and saturated into water to create a tea, or may be spread onto various foods as a spice and taste enhancer. The wood has a density of about 0.75 g/cm³.<ref>[http://www.fao.org/docrep/W4095E/w4095e0c.htm FAO Appendix 1]</ref> In [[Taiwan]], its wood is used to make support beams for [[Underground mining|underground mines]]. The wood is also converted to [[charcoal]] for family use. The plant is used in traditional medicine<ref>Li, Thomas S. C. ''Taiwanese Native Medicinal Plants: Phytopharmacology and Therapeutic Values'', CRC Press (2006), {{ISBN|0-8493-9249-7}}, p.2. [https://books.google.com/books?id=cAYXHeEPdB0C&lpg=PP1&pg=PA2#v=onepage&q&f=false online GoogleBooks preview]</ref> and is available from herbal medicine shops (草藥店) in Taiwan, but there has been no clinical study to support its effectiveness. It is also frequently used as a durable flooring material. {{multiple image | align = center | direction = horizontal | image1 = Starr 050107-2872 Acacia confusa.jpg | caption1 = ''Acacia confusa'' habit | image2 = Starr 061224-2814 Acacia confusa.jpg | caption2 = ''Acacia confusa'' leaves and pods | image3 = Acacia confusa seeds.jpg | caption3 = ''Acacia confusa'' seeds }}{{clear-left}}
== Phytochemicals == [[Phytochemical]]s found in ''Acacia confusa'':
===Root bark=== *[[N-Methyltryptamine]], 1.43%<ref name=Arthur>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1071/CH9670811| title = Nb-Methylated tryptamines and other constituents of ''Acacia'' confusa ''Merr''. Of Hong Kong| journal = Australian Journal of Chemistry| volume = 20| issue = 4| pages = 811| year = 1967| last1 = Arthur| first1 = HR| last2 = Loo| first2 = SN| last3 = Lamberton| first3 = JA}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=March 2017}} *[[dimethyltryptamine|N,N-Dimethyltryptamine]], 1.15%<ref name=Arthur/>{{Failed verification|date=March 2017}}
===Seeds===
*[[Oxalyldiaminopropionic acid]] (α-amino-β-oxalylaminopropionic acid),<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0031-9422(00)94332-2| title = The neurolathyrogen, α-amino-β-oxalylaminopropionic acid in legume seeds| journal = Phytochemistry| volume = 16| issue = 4| pages = 477| year = 1977| last1 = Quereshi| first1 = M.Yasin| last2 = Pilbeam| first2 = David J.| last3 = Evans| first3 = Christine S.| last4 = Bell| first4 = E.Arthur}}</ref> which can cause neurological damage, [[paralysis]], and death.
===Stems=== *N-Methyltryptamine, 0.04%<ref name=Arthur/>
