==History==
In 1880, in order to evade continuous persecution by the government, Tenrikyo placed itself under the administration of a [[Shugendo]] temple named Jifukuji. During this time ''Tenri-Ō-no-Mikoto'' was officially called ''Tenrin-Ō-[[Nyorai]]'' and the ''[[kanji]]'' of various other deities were changed, but by 1890 Tenrikyo was given approval by the [[Emperor Meiji|Meiji]] government and the original names were restored.<ref>Henry van Straelen. "The Religion of Divine Wisdom: Japan's Most Powerful Religious Movement." ''Folklore Studies,'' Vol. 13, (1954), pp. 1-166</ref>

