This is an incomplete list of [[Mycenaean Greece|Mycenaean Greek]] deities{{refn|group=n|This list includes deities which in later Greek times and sources were thought of as semigods or mortal heroes. Scholars assign to attested words in Linear B a possibility or probability, sometimes controversially, of being a [[theonym]] or an [[anthroponym]], a [[toponym]], etc.; Mycenaean Linear B sources are often damaged inscriptions bearing [[lacuna (manuscripts)|lacunae]], and in any case, they are too few to enable classifications with certainty.<br>Finally there is a list of attested words which seem to refer to mortals or whose reference is unclear, yet they may have a connection to religion or to a divine or heroic figure of later times.}} and of the way their names, [[epithet]]s, or titles are spelled and attested in [[Mycenaean Greek]], written in the [[Linear B]]{{refn|group=n|The names/words in Linear B and the transliteration thereof are not necessarily in the [[nominative]] [[grammatical case|case]] and also not necessarily of said gods [[Per se (terminology)|per se]], as e.g. in the case of Hephaestus.}} [[syllabary]], along with some reconstructions and equivalent forms in later [[Greek language|Greek]].

==Deities==

===Gods===
* [[Anemoi]] - attested through *''Anemohiereia'' or *''Anemon Hiereia'', "Priestess of the Winds" (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀀𐀚𐀗𐀂𐀋𐀩𐀊}}, ''a-ne-mo-i-je-re-ja'', {{lang|gmy|𐀀𐀚𐀗𐄀𐀂𐀋𐀩𐀊}}, ''a-ne-mo,i-je-re-ja'')<ref name=MRaKpage4>[[#MRaK|Gulizio (2008)]], page [https://www.academia.edu/4915183/Mycenaean_Religion_at_Knossos 4].</ref><ref name=CSaMPAaKpage206/><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/a/a-ne-mo/ a-ne-mo].</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Reflections of Women in Antiquity|editor-first=Helene P.|editor-last=Foley|publisher=Rootledge|chapter=The socio-economic roles of women in Mycenaean Greece: A brief survey from evidence of the Linear B tablets|year=2004|origyear=1981|page=15|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8T66FZciSqkC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA15#v=onepage&q&f=false|first1=Jon-Christian|last1=Billigmeier|first2=Judy A.|last2=Turner|isbn=0-677-16370-3}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=hiereia|See the [[noun]] {{lang|grc|ἱέρεια}}.<ref name=LSJhiereia>{{LSJ|i(e/reia1|ἱέρεια|ref}}.</ref>}}{{refn|group=n|name=noteKNFp1KNFp13|Found on the [[Knossos|KN]] Fp 1 and KN Fp 13 tablets.<ref name=KNFp1>[[#Damos|Dāmos]]: [https://www2.hf.uio.no/damos/Index/item/chosen_item_id/1 KN Fp 1 + 31].</ref><ref name=KNFp13>[[#Damos|Dāmos]]: [https://www2.hf.uio.no/damos/Index/item/chosen_item_id/13 KN 13 Fp(1) (138)]</ref>}}{{refn|group=n|The inscriptions read that the offers are made to her, thus they could refer to a goddess; this is not though, what modern scholars seem to believe.}}{{refn|group=n|The first cited form could just be an instance of a [[scribe]] forgetting to write the word-separator sign {{lang|gmy|𐄀}} between two words. In that case *''Anemohiereia'' should be instead read as *''Anemon Hiereia'' also.}}
* [[Ares]] (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀀𐀩}}, ''a-re'')<ref name=MRaKpage4/><ref>{{cite journal|title=A-re in the Linear B Tablets and the Continuity of the Cult of Ares in the Historical Period|url=http://www.utexas.edu/research/pasp/publications/pdf/are.pdf|first=Joann|last=Gulizio|journal=Journal of Prehistoric Religion|volume=15|pages=32–38}}</ref><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/a/a-re/ a-re].</ref><ref>[[#PAL|Palaeolexicon]]: [http://www.palaeolexicon.com/ShowWord.aspx?Id=17038 The Linear B word a-re].</ref><ref name=Haegg1997/>
* Despotas(?) - unclear, perhaps house deity (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀈𐀡𐀲}}, ''do-po-ta'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/do/do-po-ta/ do-po-ta].</ref><ref name=TMWpage95>[[#TMW|Chadwick (1976)]], page [https://books.google.com/books?id=RMj7M_tGaNMC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA95#v=onepage&q&f=false 95].</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=notePYTn316|Found on the [[Pylos|PY]] Tn 316 tablet.<ref name=refPYTn316>[[#Damos|Dāmos]]: [https://www2.hf.uio.no/damos/Index/item/chosen_item_id/4985 PY 316 Tn (44)].</ref><ref name=MSaiC>{{citation|url=http://custom.cengage.com/static_content/OLC/053427000X.bak/etep_ch03.pdf|title= Mycenaean society and its collapse|first1=Jack Martin|last1=Balcer|first2=John Matthew|last2=Stockhausen|pages=66–67}}.</ref>}}{{refn|group=n|name=despotes|[[Cf.]] the nouns {{lang|grc|[[wikt:δεσπότης|δεσπότης]], [[wikt:δόμος|δόμος]], [[wikt:πόσις|πόσις]]}};<ref name=LSJdespotes>{{LSJ|despo/ths|δεσπότης}}, {{LSJ|do/mos|δόμος}}, {{LSJ|po/sis1|πόσις|shortref}}.</ref> whence ''despot'' in English;<ref name=refOEtDdespot>{{OEtymD|despot}}</ref> in an [[etymology|etymological]] sense, it literally means "master of the house" and is related to ''potnia''.}}{{refn|group=n|name=notePoseidon-connections}}
* [[Dionysus]] (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀇𐀺𐀝𐀰}}, ''di-wo-nu-so'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref>[[#PAL|Palaeolexicon]]: [http://www.palaeolexicon.com/ShowWord.aspx?Id=17055 The Linear B word di-wo-nu-so].</ref>{{refn|group=n|According to Chadwick,<ref name=TMWpage99/> "Dionysos surprisingly appears twice at Pylos, in the form ''Diwonusos'', both times irritatingly enough on fragments, so that we have no means of verifying his divinity". This old view can be found reflected in other scholars<ref name=TMpage160/>  but this has changed after the 1989-90 Greek-Swedish [[Excavation (archaeology)|excavations]] at Kastelli Hill, Chania, unearthed the [[Chania|KH]] Gq 5 tablet.<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=AoCMpage443/><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/2012/11/02/khania-linear-b-transliterations/ Khania Linear B Transliterations].</ref><ref name=refKHGq5>[[#Damos|Dāmos]]: [https://www2.hf.uio.no/damos/Index/item/chosen_item_id/5670 KH 5 Gq (1)].</ref>}}
* Dipsioi - perhaps "the Thirsty ''and hence'' the Dead Ones"; perhaps  related to [[Ancient Thessaly|Thessalian]] month ''Dipsos'', meaning obscure (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀇𐀠𐀯𐀍𐀂}}, ''di-pi-si-jo-i'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref>{{cite book|title=Proceedings of the Cambridge Colloquium on Mycenaean Studies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s-48AAAAIAAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PA265#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher=Cambridge University Press|editor1-first=L.R.|editor1-last=Palmer|editor1-link=Leonard Robert Palmer|editor2-first=John|editor2-last=Chadwick|year=1966|pages=265–274|chapter=Πολυδίψιον Ἄργος|first=Spyridon|last=Marinatos|author-link=Spyridon Marinatos}}</ref><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/di/di-pi-si-jo/ di-pi-si-jo]</ref><ref name=TAGpage235>[[#TAG|Budin (2004)]], pages [https://books.google.gr/books?id=u-Py1QbavoQC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA235#v=onepage&q&f=false 235–236].</ref><ref name=ACtLBpage236>García-Ramón, J.L., in [[#ACtLB|Duhoux and Morpurgo Davies (2011)]], page [http://www.uni-koeln.de/phil-fak/ifl/hvs/mitarbeiter/garciaramon/pdf/82.pdf 236].</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=dipsao|Cf. the [[verb]] {{lang|grc|διψάω-ῶ}}.<ref>{{LSJ|diya/w|διψάω|shortref}}.</ref>}}
* Drimios - unknown, in later times, son of Zeus, perhaps a predecessor of [[Apollo]] (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀇𐀪𐀖𐀍}}, ''di-ri-mi-jo'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=TAGpage235/><ref name=DiMG>[[#DiMG|Ventris and Chadwick (1973)]].</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=notePYTn316}}{{refn|group=n|name=DrimiosSonOfZeus|The inscription reads (line 10): ''di-ri-mi-jo⌞ ⌟di-wo,i-je-we'', i.e. *''Drimiōi Diwos hiēwei'', "to Drimios, the son of Zeus".<ref name=refPYTn316/><ref name=ACtLBpage230/><ref>[[#PAL|Palaeolexicon]]: [http://www.palaeolexicon.com/ShowWord.aspx?Id=16761 The Linear B word i-je-we].</ref>}}
* Enesidaon - possibly a theonym; possibly an epithet of Poseidon, assumed to mean "Earthshaker" or something similar (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀁𐀚𐀯𐀅𐀃𐀚}}, ''e-ne-si-da-o-ne'')<ref name=CSaMPAaKpage206/><ref name=DiMG/><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/e/e-ne-si-da-o-ne/ e-ne-si-da-o-ne].</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=notePoseidon-connections}}{{refn|group=n|name=noteKNM719|Found on the KN M 719 tablet.<ref name=refKNM719>[[#Damos|Dāmos]]: [https://www2.hf.uio.no/damos/Index/item/chosen_item_id/655 KN 719 M (140)].</ref>}}{{refn|group=n|name=noteEnesidaon|Cf.  {{lang|grc|Ἐνοσίχθων, Ἐννοσίγαιος}}, Poseidon's later epithets.<ref name=LSJepithetsofPoseidon>{{LSJ|*)enosi/xqwn|Ἐνοσίχθων}}, {{LSJ|*)ennosi/gaios|Ἐννοσίγαιος|shortref}}.</ref>}}
* [[Enyalius]] - a later epithet of Ares  (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀁𐀝𐀷𐀪𐀍}}, ''e-nu-wa-ri-jo'')<ref name=CSaMPAaKpage206/><ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=TMpage160>[[#TM|Schofield (2007)]], page [https://books.google.com/books?id=QXwzT1048Z4C&lpg=PA1&pg=PA160#v=onepage&q&f=false 160].</ref><ref name=TAGpage235/>
* [[Hephaestus]] - regarded as indirectly attested by the name *''Haphaistios'' or *''Haphaistion'', presumed to be a [[theophoric name]] (Linear B:  {{lang|gmy|𐀀𐀞𐀂𐀴𐀍}}, ''a-pa-i-ti-jo'')<ref name=TMWpage99>[[#TMW|Chadwick (1976)]], page [https://books.google.com/books?id=RMj7M_tGaNMC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA99#v=onepage&q&f=false 99].</ref><ref name=AoCMpage443/><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/a/a-pa-i-ti-jo/ a-pa-i-ti-jo].</ref>
* [[Hermes]] (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀁𐀔𐁀}}, ''e-ma-*25'' or ''e-ma-ha'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=ACtLBpage230>García-Ramón, J.L., in [[#ACtLB|Duhoux and Morpurgo Davies (2011)]], page [http://www.uni-koeln.de/phil-fak/ifl/hvs/mitarbeiter/garciaramon/pdf/82.pdf 230].</ref><ref name=refHaE>[[#HaE|Gulizio (2000)]].</ref><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/e/e-ma-a2/ e-ma-a2].</ref><ref name=PaLemaha>[[#PAL|Palaeolexicon]]: [http://www.palaeolexicon.com/ShowWord.aspx?Id=17020 The Linear B word e-ma-ha].</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=noteErmahas|{{lang|gmy|𐀁𐀔𐁀}}, when in the nominative, is thought to be read as {{lang|grc|Ἑρμάἁς (Ἑρμάhας)}}.<ref name=refHaEpage106>[[#HaE|Gulizio (2000)]], page [http://www.utexas.edu/research/pasp/publications/pdf/hermes.pdf 106].</ref>}}
** Areias - epithet (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀀𐀩𐀊}}, ''a-re-ja'')<ref name=ACtLBpage230/><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/a/a-re-ja/ a-re-ja].</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=notePYTn316}}
* Marineus(?) - unknown deity, perhaps "God of the Woolens", meaning obscure (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀔𐀪𐀚}}, ''ma-ri-ne(-u?)'', {{lang|gmy|𐀔𐀪𐀚𐀸}}, ma-ri-ne-we, {{lang|gmy|𐀔𐀪𐀚𐀺}}, ma-ri-ne-wo)<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=TMWpage99/><ref name=AoCMpage443>[[#AoCM|Trzaskoma et al (2004)]], page [https://books.google.com/books?id=K4pZr3JfYqcC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA443#v=onepage&q&f=false 443–446].</ref><ref name=TKNpage122>[[#TKL|Castleden (2003)]], page [https://books.google.com/books?id=GupJUn_xqkkC&pg&lpg=PP1&pg=PA122#v=onepage&q&f=false 122].</ref><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/ma/ma-ri-ne/ ma-ri-ne], [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/ma/ma-ri-ne-we/ ma-ri-ne-we].</ref>
* Pade(?) - possibly unknown god, thought to be Cretan, [[Minoan civilization|Minoan]] in origin (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀞𐀆}} ''pa-de'', {{lang|gmy|𐀞𐀆𐀂}} ''pa-de-i'')<ref name=MRaKpage4/><ref name=CSaMPAaKpage206/><ref name=Haegg1997>[[#HAEGG|Hägg (1997)]], page [http://cefael.efa.gr/detail.php?site_id=1&actionID=page&serie_id=BCHSuppl&volume_number=30&ce=l6chj93l367b20bjj46cra1t214ql5jl&sp=173 165].</ref><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/pa/pa-de/ pa-de].</ref>
* [[Paean (god)|Paean]]  - a precursor of Apollo (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀞𐀊𐀺𐀚}}, ''pa-ja-wo-ne'')<ref name=CSaMPAaKpage206/><ref name=Haegg1997/><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/linear-b-transliterations/knossos/kn-v/kn-v/#toc-kn-v-52 KN V 52+].</ref><ref name=TMWpage89>[[#TMW|Chadwick (1976)]], page [https://books.google.com/books?id=RMj7M_tGaNMC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA89#v=onepage&q&f=false 89].</ref>{{refn|group=n|Hiller's<ref name=CSaMPAaKpage206/> or Schofield's<ref name=TMpage160/>  ''pa-ja-wo'' is not actually attested per se; the word actually attested on the damaged KN V 52 tablet and the fragments thereof, reads ''pa-ja-wo-ne''; the latter would be the [[dative case]] form of the former.<ref name=TMWpage89/><ref name=refKNV52>[[#Damos|Dāmos]]: [https://www2.hf.uio.no/damos/Index/item/chosen_item_id/49 KN 52 V + 52 bis + 8285 (unknown)].</ref>}}
* [[Poseidon]] - chief deity  (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀡𐀮𐀆𐀃}}, ''po-se-da-o'', {{lang|gmy|𐀡𐀮𐀆𐀺𐀚}}, ''po-se-da-wo-ne'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=Poseidon&Erinys>{{cite book|title=Δώρον. Τιμητικός Τόμος για τον καθηγητή Σπύρο Ιακωβίδη|trans-title=''[[Festschrift]] for Spyros Iakovides''|editor-first=Despoina|editor-last=Danielidou|place=Athens|year=2009|chapter=Continuity from the Mycenaean Period in a historical Boeotian Cult of Poseidon (and Erinys)|first=Thomas G.|last=Palaima|author-link=Thomas G. Palaima|pages=527–536|series=Σειρά Μονογραφιών. 6|publisher=[[Academy of Athens (modern)|Academy of Athens]]|chapter-url=http://www.utexas.edu/research/pasp/publications/pdf/continuity.pdf}}</ref><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/po/po-se-da-o/ po-se-da-o].</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=notePoseidon-connections|The word ''Poseidon'' ({{lang|grc|Ποσειδῶν}}; variant forms include {{lang|grc|Ποσειδάων}}, the former's final syllable being a [[synaeresis]] of the latter's final two) itself, could be connected in an etymological sense - cf. {{lang|grc|πόσις}} - to ''Despotas'' (if indeed this is the correct reading-interpretation of ''do-po-ta'') and ''Potnia'';<ref name=TAGpage235/> likewise compare the same word in connection to ''Ge''-''Gaia'' (hence possibly to ''Ma Ga'') and the possible ''Enesidaon'' and other undoubted later-times epithets of him, in consideration of the word-endings, etc.. Moreover some scholars have connected - in a similar manner to the one of ''Poseidon'' - ''Demeter'' to "Earth" via the ''De'' (''Da''; considered in this case as [[Pre-Greek substrate|Pre-Greek]] and as meaning "Earth") syllable, the goddess thus viewed as representing ''Da''-''Mater'', "Mother Earth" or similar; others on the other hand have interpreted ''Demeter''{{'}}s ''Da'' syllable as related to ''domos'' (i.e. to be [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]]), interpreting her name as "Mother of the House", creating thus an etymological connection to ''Despotas'' and ''Potnia''. À propos, some scholars have considered the attested, on the PY En 609 tablet,<ref name=refPYEn609>[[#Damos|Dāmos]]: [https://www2.hf.uio.no/damos/Index/item/chosen_item_id/4560 PY 609 En].</ref> Mycenaean word {{lang|gmy|𐀅𐀔𐀳}}, ''da-ma-te'', as reading ''Demeter'', but the view isn't widely held anymore; the former is indeed thought to be connected to ''domos'', etc, but it is believed to probably be a form of, or something similar to, {{lang|grc|δάμαρ}}.<ref name=LSJposeidon>{{LSJ|*poseidw{{=}}n|Ποσειδών|shortref}}.</ref><ref name=BeekesPoseidon>{{cite book|title=Etymological Dictionary of Greek|first=Robert|last=Beekes|author-link=Robert S. P. Beekes|others=With the assistance of Lucien van Beek. In two volumes.|place=Leiden, Boston|year=2010|origyear=2009|chapter=E.g., [[s.v.]] {{lang|grc|γαῖα, δάμαρ, πόσις, Δημήτηρ}}|isbn=9789004174184}}</ref><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/da/da-ma-te/ da-ma-te].</ref><ref name=LSJdamar>{{LSJ|da/mar|δάμαρ|shortref}}.</ref>}}
* Trisheros - theonym, "Thrice-Hero"; thought to attest, and pertain to, the [[veneration of the dead]] (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀴𐀪𐀮𐀫𐀁}}, ''ti-ri-se-ro-e'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=TAGpage235/><ref>[[#PAL|Palaeolexicon]]: [http://www.palaeolexicon.com/ShowWord.aspx?Id=17018 The Linear B word ti-ri-se-ro-e].</ref><ref name=RKAtrisheros>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/ti/ti-ri-se-ro-e/ ti-ri-se-ro-e].</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.threes.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2890:thrice-hero&catid=82:mythology&Itemid=62|title= Thrice-Hero | accessdate=2012-04-27|website=The Book of Threes|first=Alena|last=Trckova-Flamee}}</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=notePYTn316PYFr1204|Found on the PY Tn 316 and PY Fr 1204 tablets.<ref name=refPYTn316/><ref name=refPYFr1204>[[#Damos|Dāmos]]: [https://www2.hf.uio.no/damos/Index/item/chosen_item_id/4633 PY 1204 Fr (4)].</ref>}}{{refn|group=n|name=noteTrisheros|See the words {{lang|grc|τρίς, ἥρως}}.<ref name=LSJtris>{{LSJ|tri/s|τρίς|shortref}}.</ref><ref name=LSJheros>{{LSJ|h(/rws|ἥρως|shortref}}.</ref><ref>{{OEtymD|hero}}</ref>}}{{refn|group=n|It is generally thought to be connected to {{lang|grc|τριπάτορες}}, i.e. the "collective, anonymous family ancestors",<ref name=RKAtrisheros/><ref name=tripatores>{{cite journal|journal=Rencontres d'archéologie de l'IFEA|url=http://hal.inria.fr/docs/00/80/82/17/PDF/05_Herda.pdf|page=105|first=Alexander|last=Herda|title=Burying a Sage: The Heroon of Thales in the Agora of Miletos|year=2011|place=Istanbul|publisher=Institut français d'études anatoliennes}}</ref><ref name=LSJtripator>{{LSJ|tripa/twr|τριπάτωρ|shortref}}.</ref> but it could perhaps instead refer to [[Triptolemus]], himself possibly "a ‘[[wikt:hypostasis|hypostasis]]’ of Poseidon".<ref name=tripatores/><ref name=Triptolemos>{{citation|first=Martin|last=Peters|chapter=Aus der Vergangenheit von Heroen und Ehegöttinnen|editor1-first=Matthias|editor1-last=Fritz|editor2-first=Susanne|editor2-last=Zeifelder|title=Novalis Indogermanica: Festschrift für Günter Neumann zum 80. Geburstag|place=Graz|series=Grazer vergleichende Arbeiten|publisher=Leykam|year=2002|pages=357–380|language=German|isbn=3701100322}}.</ref>}}
* [[Anax]] - "the King"; in this case, it is considered to be a theonym in the dative case, perhaps as an epithet of Zeus (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀷𐀙𐀏𐀳}}, ''wa-na-ka-te'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=TAGpage235/><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/wa/wa-na-ka/ wa-na-ka].</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=ttKttTQ|The King and the Two Queens are sometimes attested on tablets together, in the offerings or the [[libation]]s to them; forms of both "the King" and "the Two Queens" are in the dative case. An example of said concurrent attested worship is the PY Fr 1227 tablet.<ref name=refPYFr1227>[[#Damos|Dāmos]]: [https://www2.hf.uio.no/damos/Index/item/chosen_item_id/4653 PY 1227 Fr (2)].</ref>}}{{refn|group=n|name=mortalroyalty|On the other hand, there are scholars who have argued that "the King" and "the Two Queens" are not theonyms, that they simply refer to mortal royalty.<ref name=AGftMPttAoHpage66/>}}
* [[Zeus]] - God of the sky (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀇𐀸}}, ''di-we'', {{lang|gmy|𐀇𐀺}}, ''di-wo'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/di/di-we/ di-we].</ref><ref>[[#PAL|Palaeolexicon]]:[http://www.palaeolexicon.com/ShowWord.aspx?Id=16703 The Linear B word di-we]; [http://www.palaeolexicon.com/ShowWord.aspx?Id=16635 The Linear B word di-wo].</ref>
** Diktaios - local epithet of Zeus on [[Crete]] (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀇𐀏𐀲𐀍 𐀇𐀸}}, ''di-ka-ta-jo di-we'')<ref name=MRaKpage4/><ref name=Haegg1997/><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/di/di-ka-ta/ di-ka-ta].</ref><ref>[[#PAL|Palaeolexicon]]: [http://www.palaeolexicon.com/ShowWord.aspx?Id=17107 The Linear B word di-ka-ta-jo].</ref>{{refn|group=n|Pertaining to the [[Dikti]].<ref name=LSJdiktaios>{{LSJ|*diktai{{=}}os|Δικταῖος|shortref}}.</ref>}}{{refn|group=n|name=noteKNFp1|Found on the KN Fp 1 tablet.<ref name=KNFp1/>}}

===Goddesses===
* [[Artemis]] (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀀𐀳𐀖𐀵}}, ''a-te-mi-to'', {{lang|gmy| 𐀀𐀴𐀖𐀳}}, ''a-ti-mi-te'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref>{{cite journal|first1=John|last1=Chadwick|first2=Lydia|last2=Baumbach|title=The Mycenaean Greek Vocabulary|journal=Glotta|volume='''41'''.3&4|year=1963|pages=157–271, p. 176f; s.v. Ἂρτεμις|quote=''a-te-mi-to-'' (genitive)}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|first=C.|last=Souvinous|title=A-TE-MI-TO and A-TI-MI-TE|journal=Kadmos|volume=9|year= 1970|pages=42–47|doi=10.1515/kadm.1970.9.1.42}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|first=T.|last=Christidis|title=Further remarks on A-TE-MI-TO and A-TI-MI-TE|journal=Kadmos|volume='''11'''.2|pages=125–28|year=1972}}</ref><ref>[[#PAL|Palaeolexicon]]: [http://www.palaeolexicon.com/ShowWord.aspx?Id=17019 The Linear B word a-ti-mi-te].</ref>
* Diwia - possibly the female counterpart of Zeus, possibly [[Dione (mythology)|Dione]] in later Greek (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀇𐀄𐀊}}, ''di-u-ja'', {{lang|gmy|𐀇𐀹𐀊}}, ''di-wi-ja'')<ref name=CSaMPAaKpage206/><ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=TMWpage95/><ref name=TAGpage235/>
* Doqeia(?) - possibly an unknown goddess but could be only a feminine [[adjective]] (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀈𐀤𐀊}}, ''do-qe-ja'')<ref name=FromAtD>Nosch, Marie Louise, in [[#FAtD|Fischer-Hansen and Poulsen (2009)]], page [https://books.google.com/books?id=2garBSREfywC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA22#v=onepage&q&f=false 22].</ref><ref name=DAISPalaima>{{cite conference|chapter-url=http://www.utexas.edu/research/pasp/publications/pdf/PalaimaDais.pdf|first=Thomas G.|last=Palaima|chapter=The Siginificance of Mycenaean Words Relating to Meals, Meal Rituals and Food|editor1-first=Louise A.|editor1-last=Hitchcock|editor2-first=Robert|editor2-last=Laffineur|editor3-first=Janice|editor3-last=Crowley|title=''DAIS The Aegean Feast''. Proceedings of the 12th International Aegean Conference|conference=12th International Aegean Conference. University of Melbourne|origyear=Date of Conference: 25–29 March 2008|journal=Aegaeum|year=2008|place=Liège, Austin|pages=383–389}}</ref><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/do/do-qe-ja/ do-qe-ja].</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=notePYAn607|Found on the PY An 607 tablet.<ref name=refPYAn607>[[#Damos|Dāmos]]: [https://www2.hf.uio.no/damos/Index/item/chosen_item_id/4349 PY 607 An (1)].</ref>}}
* [[Eileithyia]] - attested in the Cretan ''Eleuthia'' form; perhaps Minoan in origin (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀁𐀩𐀄𐀴𐀊}}, ''e-re-u-ti-ja'')<ref name=CSaMPAaKpage206/><ref name=Haegg1997/><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/linear-b-transliterations/knossos/kn-g/kn-gg/ KN Gg 705], [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/linear-b-transliterations/knossos/kn-o/kn-od/ KN Od 714+].</ref><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/e/e-re-u-ti-ja/ e-re-u-ti-ja].</ref><ref>[[#PAL|Palaeolexicon]]: [http://www.palaeolexicon.com/ShowWord.aspx?Id=16730 The Linear B word e-re-u-ti-ja].</ref>
* [[Erinyes]] - both forms of the theonym are considered to be in the [[grammatical number|singular]], ''Erinys'' (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀁𐀪𐀝}}, ''e-ri-nu'', {{lang|gmy|𐀁𐀪𐀝𐀸}}, ''e-ri-nu-we'')<ref name=MRaKpage4/><ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=Poseidon&Erinys/><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/e/e-ri-nu/ e-ri-nu].</ref><ref>[[#PAL|Palaeolexicon]]: [http://www.palaeolexicon.com/ShowWord.aspx?Id=17056 The Linear B word e-ri-nu-we].</ref>{{refn|group=n|Found on the KN Fp 1, KN V 52, and KN Fh 390 tablets.<ref name=refKNV52/><ref>[[#Damos|Dāmos]]: [https://www2.hf.uio.no/damos/Index/item/chosen_item_id/1 KN 1 Fp(1) + 31 (138)], [https://www2.hf.uio.no/damos/Index/item/chosen_item_id/371 KN 390 Fh (141)].</ref>}}
* [[Hera]] (Linear B:  {{lang|gmy|𐀁𐀨}}, ''[[wiktionary:𐀁𐀨|e-ra]]'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=TAGpage235/><ref>[[#PAL|Palaeolexicon]]: [http://www.palaeolexicon.com/ShowWord.aspx?Id=16725 The Linear B word e-ra].</ref>
* Iphemedeia - theonym; probably variant form of [[Iphimedia]], name of a [[Greek mythology|mythological]] person found in [[Homer]]'s ''[[Odyssey]]'' (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀂𐀟𐀕𐀆𐀊}}, ''i-pe-me-de-ja'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=TMWpage95/><ref name=TAGpage235/><ref>[[#PAL|Palaeolexicon]]: [http://www.palaeolexicon.com/ShowWord.aspx?Id=17017 The Linear B word i-pe-me-de-ja].</ref>
* Komawenteia(?) - possibly unknown deity, possibly meaning "long-haired goddess" (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀒𐀔𐀸𐀳𐀊}} ''ko-ma-we-te-ja'')<ref name=TMWpage95/><ref>[[#PAL|Palaeolexicon]]: [http://www.palaeolexicon.com/ShowWord.aspx?Id=16640 ko-ma-we-te-ja].</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=Kome|Cf. ''ko-ma-we'', {{lang|grc|κομήεις, κόμη}}.<ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/ko/ko-ma-we/ ko-ma-we].</ref><ref name=LSJkome>{{LSJ|ko/mh|κόμη|shortref}}.</ref>}}
* Manasa - unknown goddess (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀔𐀙𐀭}}, ''ma-na-sa'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=TAGpage235/><ref name=FromAtD/><ref name=TKNpage112>[[#TKL|Castleden (2003)]], page [https://books.google.com/books?id=GupJUn_xqkkC&pg&lpg=PP1&pg=PA112#v=onepage&q&f=false 112].</ref><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/ma/ma-na-sa/ ma-na-sa].</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=notePYTn316}}{{refn|group=n|name=Manasa|Cf. the [[Hinduism|Hindu goddess]] of the [[Manasa|same name]].}}
* Mater Theia - possibly "Mother of the Gods" or [[mother goddess]] (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀔𐀳𐀩𐄀𐀳𐀂𐀊}}, ''ma-te-re,te-i-ja'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timelessmyths.com/classical/mother.html|title=Mother Goddesses|website=Timeless Myths: Classical Mythology}}</ref><ref name=GRpage44/>{{refn|group=n|name=theia|See the nouns {{lang|grc|μήτηρ, θεός, θεά}} and the adjective {{lang|grc|θεῖος-α-ον}}.<ref name=LSJmater>{{LSJ|mh/thr|μήτηρ|shortref}}.</ref><ref name=LSJtheos>{{LSJ|qei{{=}}os1|θεῖος-α-ον}}, {{LSJ|qeo/s|θεός}}, {{LSJ|qea/1|θεά|shortref}}.</ref>}}
* Pipituna - unknown deity, considered to be Pre-Greek or Minoan (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀠𐀠𐀶𐀙}}, ''pi-pi-tu-na'')<ref name=MRaKpage4/><ref name=CSaMPAaKpage206/><ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=ACtLBpage236/><ref name=DiMG/><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/linear-b-transliterations/knossos/kn-f/kn-fp/ KN Fp 13].</ref><ref>[[#PAL|Palaeolexicon]]: [http://www.palaeolexicon.com/ShowWord.aspx?Id=16858 The Linear B word pi-pi-tu-na].</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=Diktynna|Cf. ''[[Diktynna]]'' about word formation, considered to be characteristically Pre-Greek.<ref name=ACtLBpage236/><ref name=Haegg1997page166>[[#HAEGG|Hägg (1997)]], page [http://cefael.efa.gr/detail.php?site_id=1&actionID=page&serie_id=BCHSuppl&volume_number=30&ce=l6chj93l367b20bjj46cra1t214ql5jl&sp=174 166].</ref>}}
* Posidaeia - probably the female counterpart to Poseidon (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀡𐀯𐀅𐀁𐀊}}, ''po-si-da-e-ja'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=TMWpage95/>{{refn|group=n|name=notePYTn316}}
* [[Potnia]] - “Mistress” or “Lady”; may be used as an epithet for many deities, but also shows up as a single deity (Linear B:  {{lang|gmy|𐀡𐀴𐀛𐀊}}, ''po-ti-ni-ja'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/po/po-ti-ni-ja/Po-ti-ni-ja Po-ti-ni-ja].</ref><ref>[[#PAL|Palaeolexicon]]: [http://www.palaeolexicon.com/ShowWord.aspx?Id=16633  The Linear B word po-ti-ni-ja].</ref><ref name=LSJpotnia>{{LSJ|po/tnia|πότνια|shortref}}.</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=notePoseidon-connections}}
** Potnia [[Athena]] - or Potnia of ''At(h)ana'' (''Athens''(?)); reference of the latter is uncertain (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀀𐀲𐀙𐀡𐀴𐀛𐀊}}, ''a-ta-na-po-ti-ni-ja'')<ref name=CSaMPAaKpage206/><ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=GRpage44>[[#GR|Burkert (1985)]], page  [https://books.google.com/books?id=sxurBtx6shoC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA44#v=onepage&q&f=false 44].</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=noteKNV52|Found on the KN V 52 tablet.<ref name=refKNV52/>}}
** Potnia [[Hippeia]] - Mistress of the Horses; later epithet of [[Demeter]] and Athena (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀡𐀴𐀛𐀊𐄀𐀂𐀤𐀊}}, ''po-ti-ni-ja,i-qe-ja'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=GRpage44/>{{refn|group=n|name=hippeia|See the words {{lang|grc|ἵππειος-α-ον, ἵππος}}.<ref name=LSJhippeia>{{LSJ|i(/ppeios|ἵππειος-α-ον}}, {{LSJ|i(/ppos|ἵππος|shortref}}.</ref>}}{{refn|group=n|Could also be precursor of [[Leto]].{{citation needed|date=March 2014}}}}
** Potnia of Sitos - Mistress of Grain, [[Bronze Age]] predecessor or epithet of Demeter (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀯𐀵𐀡𐀴𐀛𐀊}}, ''si-to-po-ti-ni-ja'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=FromAtD/><ref name=GRpage44/><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/si/si-to-po-ti-ni-ja/ si-to-po-ti-ni-ja].</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=sitos|See the noun [[wikt:σῖτος|σῖτος]] and the epithet {{lang|grc|Σιτώ}}.<ref name=LSJsitos>{{LSJ|si{{=}}tos|σῖτος}}, {{LSJ|*sitw/|Σιτώ|shortref}}.</ref>}}
** Potnia of the [[Labyrinth#Cretan labyrinth|Labyrinth]] (Linear B: {{lang|gmy| 𐀅𐁆𐀪𐀵𐀍𐄀𐀡𐀴𐀛𐀊}}, ''da-pu<sub>2</sub>-ri-to-jo,po-ti-ni-ja'')<ref name=CSaMPAaKpage206/><ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=TAGpage235/><ref name=GRpage44/>
** Potnia, at [[Thebes, Greece|Thebes]], of no attested name or title, other than that offers are made ''to'' her ''house'', her ''premises'' (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀡𐀴𐀛𐀊𐄀𐀺𐀒𐀆}}, ''po-ti-ni-ja,wo-ko-de'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=TMWpage99/><ref name=TAGpage235/><ref name=FromAtDpage31/><ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/wo/wo-ko-de/ wo-ko-de].</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=THnamelessPotnia|Said Potnia or ''Potnia'' in general is found on only one table at Thebes: [[Thebes, Greece|TH]] Of 36.<ref name=refTHOf36>[[#Damos|Dāmos]]: [https://www2.hf.uio.no/damos/Index/item/collection_id/3/chosen_item_id/5435 TH Of 36 (303)].</ref> Her ''premises'', her ''house'' is thought to have been her shrine.<ref name=TMWpage99/><ref name=FromAtDpage31>Nosch, Marie Louise, in [[#FAtD|Fischer-Hansen and Poulsen (2009)]], page [https://books.google.com/books?id=2garBSREfywC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA31#v=onepage&q&f=false 31].</ref>}}
** Potnia, of unidentified [[Pylos]] sanctuary - unknown local(?) goddess of  ''pa-ki-ja-ne'' (*''Sphagianes''?) [[sanctuary]] at Pylos (Linear B:  {{lang|gmy|𐀡𐀴𐀛𐀊}}, ''po-ti-ni-ja'')<ref name=GRpage44/><ref name="dartmouth.edu">{{cite web|publisher=Dartmouth College|website=Aegean Prehistoric Archaeology|url=http://www.dartmouth.edu/~prehistory/aegean/?page_id=651|title=Lesson 26: Narrative. Mycenaean and Late Cycladic Religion and Religious Architecture}}</ref><ref name=RKApakijane>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/pa/pa-ki-ja-ne/ pa-ki-ja-ne].</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=notePYTn316}}{{refn|group=n|name=HumanSacrificeViews|The word, on the same tablet, {{lang|gmy|𐀡𐀩𐀙}}, ''po-re-na'', *''phorenas'', understood to mean "those brought ''or'' those bringing" (it actually reads {{lang|gmy|𐀡𐀩𐀙𐀤}}, ''po-re-na-qe'', but a postfixed {{lang|gmy|𐀤}}, ''qe'', is usually a [[conjunction (grammar)|conjunction]]; cf. {{lang|grc|καί, τε}}, and [[Latin]] ''et'', ''qve''),<ref name=LSJkai-te>{{LSJ|kai/1|καί}}, {{LSJ|te1|τε|shortref}}.</ref><ref name=L&Set-qve>''{{L&S|et}}'', {{L&S|que|''qve''|ref}}</ref> has been interpreted by some scholars as evidence of human sacrifice at said sanctuary:<ref name=refHaEpage107>[[#HaE|Gulizio (2000)]], pages [http://www.utexas.edu/research/pasp/publications/pdf/hermes.pdf 107–108].</ref> "According to this interpretation, the text of Tn 316 was written as one of many extreme emergency measures just before the destruction of the palace. Tn 316 would then reflect a desperate, and abnormal, attempt to placate divine powers through the sacrifice of male victims to male gods and female victims to female gods".<ref name=AoCMpage450>[[#AoCM|Trzaskoma et al (2004)]], page [https://books.google.com/books?id=K4pZr3JfYqcC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA450#v=onepage&q&f=false 450].</ref>}}{{refn|group=n|name=pakijasi-potnia|The nominative case form of the place (i.e. of the sanctuary) is {{lang|gmy|𐀞𐀑𐀊𐀚}}, ''pa-ki-ja-ne''; it is also found in other forms, including derivative words; the specific form found on the PY Tn 316 tablet is {{lang|gmy|𐀞𐀑𐀊𐀯}}, ''pa-ki-ja-si'', i.e. possibly its [[locative]] plural form.<ref name=RKApakijane/>}}
** Potnia, of uncertain ''A'' place or epithet (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀡𐀴𐀛𐀊𐄀𐀀𐀯𐀹𐀊}}, ''po-ti-ni-ja,a-si-wi-ja'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=Asian>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/a/a-si-wi-ja/ a-si-wi-ja], [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/a/a-64-ja/ a-*64-ja].</ref>{{refn|group=n|Possibly an [[ethnonym|ethnic]] or geographic adjective of Asia understood in this context as referring to [[Lydia]] or the [[Assuwa league]]; i.e. in the sense of, or similar to, [[Anatolia]].<ref name=Asian/>}}{{refn|group=n|Perhaps an epithet of Artemis.}}
** Potnia, of unknown ''E'' place or epithet (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀁𐀩𐀹𐀍𐀡𐀴𐀛𐀊}}, ''e-re-wi-jo-po-ti-ni-ja'')<ref name=FromAtD/>{{refn|group=n|Perhaps an epithet of Hera.{{citation needed|date=March 2014|reason=This probably has to do with a possible connection of 'e-re-wi-jo' to 'e-ra'; still, sources are needed.}}}}
** Potnia, of unknown ''N'' place or epithet (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀚𐀺𐀟𐀃𐄀𐀡𐀴𐀛𐀊}}, ''ne-wo-pe-o,po-ti-ni-ja'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=FromAtD/>
** Potnia, of unknown ''U'' place or epithet (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀄𐀡𐀍𐀡𐀴𐀛𐀊}}, ''u-po-jo-po-ti-ni-ja'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=FromAtD/>{{refn|group=n|Could be some kind of "under" or "to weave" epithet;<ref name=FromAtD/> cf. the [[preposition]] {{lang|grc|ὑπό}} and the verb {{lang|grc|ὑφαίνω}}.<ref name=LSJhypo>{{LSJ|u(po/|ὑπό|shortref}}.</ref><ref name=LSJhyphaino>{{LSJ|u(fai/nw|ὑφαίνω|shortref}}.</ref>}}
** Potnia, of unknown ''?'' place or epithet (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀀𐀐𐀯𐄀𐀡𐀴𐀛𐀊}}, ''(?)-a-ke-si,po-ti-ni-ja'')<ref name=FromAtD/>{{refn|group=n|name=notePYAn1281|Found on the PY An 1281 tablet.<ref name=refPYAn1281>[[#Damos|Dāmos]]: [https://www2.hf.uio.no/damos/Index/item/chosen_item_id/4361 PY 1281 An + frr.: 10 + fr. (12)].</ref>}}
* Preswa(?) - generally interpreted as a dove goddess or an early form of [[Persephone]] (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀟𐀩𐁚}}, ''pe-re-*82'' or ''pe-re-swa'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=TMWpage95/><ref name=TKNpage112/><ref name=GRpage45>[[#GR|Burkert (1985)]], pages  [https://books.google.com/books?id=sxurBtx6shoC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA45#v=onepage&q&f=false 45], [https://books.google.com/books?id=sxurBtx6shoC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA364#v=onepage&q&f=false 364].</ref>
* Qerasia(?) - unknown goddess, perhaps Minoan in origin or possibly connected with ''thēr'' (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀤𐀨𐀯𐀊}}, ''qe-ra-si-ja'')<ref name=MRaKpage4/><ref name=CSaMPAaKpage206/><ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=TAGpage235/><ref name=FromAtD/><ref name=therProcMS>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s-48AAAAIAAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PA30#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=29|chapter=The Olive Oil tablets of Knossos|first=John|last=Chadwick|title=Proceedings of the Cambridge Colloquium on Mycenaean Studies|editor1-first=L.R.|editor1-last=Palmer|editor2-first=John|editor2-last=Chadwick|year=1966|publisher=Cambridge University Press}}</ref><ref name=TherRKA>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/qe/qe-ra-si-ja/ qe-ra-si-ja].</ref><ref name=PALqerasia>[[#PAL|Palaeolexicon]]: [http://www.palaeolexicon.com/ShowWord.aspx?Id=17109 The Linear B word qe-ra-si-ja].</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=ther|Possibly an epithet of Artemis; cf. {{lang|grc|[[Potnia Theron|Πότνια θηρῶν]]}}, {{lang|grc|θήρ}}.<ref name=PALqerasia/><ref name=LSJther>{{LSJ|qh/r|θήρ|shortref}}.</ref><ref name=FromAtD22-3>Nosch, Marie Louise, in [[#FAtD|Fischer-Hansen and Poulsen (2009)]], pages [https://books.google.com/books?id=2garBSREfywC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA22#v=onepage&q&f=false 22–23].</ref>}}{{refn|group=n|name=Teiresias|Could be instead, form of [[Tiresias]].{{citation needed|date=March 2014}}}}
* Qowia(?) - unknown deity, possibly meaning “She of the Cow(s)" (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀦𐀹𐀊}}, ''qo-wi-ja'')<ref name=TMWpage95/><ref name=AGftMPttAoHpage66>[[#WaRPTiMalG|Palaima (2006)]], page [http://www.utexas.edu/research/pasp/publications/pdf/wanaks.pdf 66].</ref><ref name=FromAtD/>{{refn|group=n|name=notePYTn316}}{{refn|group=n|name=bous|Cf. the noun [[wikt:βοῦς|βοῦς]].<ref name=LSJbous>{{LSJ|bou{{=}}s|βοῦς|shortref}}.</ref>}}{{refn|group=n|Perhaps connected to proposed [[Proto-Indo-European language|PIE]] *''Gʷouu̯indā''; cf. ''[[Govinda]]'' and [[Old Irish]] ''Boand''.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Campanile|first=Enrico|title=Old Irish ''Boand''|journal=[[Journal of Indo-European Studies]]|volume='''13'''.3&4|year=1985|pages=477–479}}</ref>}}
* Wanasse(?) - "the Two [[Anax|Queens]]", possibly Demeter and Persephone, *''wanassoin''(?) regarded as a dative [[Dual (grammatical number)|dual]] form (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀷𐀙𐀰𐀂}}, ''wa-na-so-i'')<ref name=Haegg1997/><ref name=TAGpage235/><ref name="dartmouth.edu"/>{{refn|group=n|name=ttKttTQ}}{{refn|group=n|name=mortalroyalty}}

===Pantheon===
*Pantes Theoi - a special invocation "to All the Gods", irrespectively of sex, etc.; recurrently attested at Knossos (Linear B : {{lang|gmy|𐀞𐀯𐀳𐀃𐀂}}, ''pa-si-te-o-i'')<ref name=CSaMPAaKpage206>[[#HILLER|Hiller (1997)]], page [http://cefael.efa.gr/detail.php?site_id=1&actionID=page&serie_id=BCHSuppl&volume_number=30&max_image_size=850&x=11&y=15&ce=tou8cjto0scf1ncaie1tjeq8006dkk5e&sp=214 206].</ref><ref name=ACtLBpage230/><ref name=MRaKpage3>[[#MRaK|Gulizio (2008)]], page [https://www.academia.edu/4915183/Mycenaean_Religion_at_Knossos 3][[wikt:ff.#Abbreviation|ff.]].</ref><ref name=refPasiTheoi1>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/pa/pa-si-te-o-i/ pa-si-te-o-i].</ref>{{refn|group=n|name=notePantheon1|This term is for example found, on the Kn Fp 1 and KN Fp 13 tablets.<ref name=KNFp1/><ref name=KNFp13/>}}{{refn|group=n|name=notePantheon2|It should be made clear that an absence of offerings, in parallel, to explicitly named deities or people (like priests or priestesses) on relevant attested inscriptions, does not necessarily follow from the presence of this special dedication; for example, the Kn Fp 1 inscription also includes, among others, offerings to Zeus Diktaios, Pade, Erinys and Anemon Hiereia.}}{{refn|group=n|name=notePantheon3|The words are two - despite the lack of a separator symbol - and in the dative plural case; their reconstructed form is *''pansi tʰeoihi''; see the words {{lang|grc|[[wikt:πᾶς|πᾶς]], [[wikt:θεός|θεός]]}}.<ref name=ACtLBpage230/><ref name=LSJtheos/><ref name=LSJpas>{{LSJ|pa{{=}}s1|πᾶς|shortref}}.</ref>}}

==Heroes, mortals and other entities or concepts==
* Proteus - could be the theonym of the sea-god [[Proteus]], but probably just the anthroponym of a nobleman (Linear B: {{lang|gmy|𐀡𐀫𐀳𐀄}}, ''po-ro-te-u'')<ref>[[#RKA|Linear B Transliterations]]: [http://minoan.deaditerranean.com/resources/linear-b-sign-groups/po/po-ro-te-u/ po-ro-te-u].</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Recherches en linquistique grecque|editor-first=Christos|editor-last=Clairis|isbn=2-7475-2742-5|first=Antonin|last=Bartoněk|chapter=Mycenaean words in Homer|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KKWlkCfX1ZsC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA94#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=94|publisher=L'Harmattan|year=2002}}</ref><ref>[[#PAL|Palaeolexicon]]: [http://www.palaeolexicon.com/ShowWord.aspx?Id=16869 The Linear B word po-ro-te-u].</ref>

==Deities speculated to have been worshipped but without hitherto attestation in the Linear B tablets==
* A possible [[sun goddess]], predecessor to [[Helios]] and possibly related to ''Helen''.<ref>{{cite book|first1=Kristian|last1=Kristiansen|first2=Thomas B.|last2=Larsson|title=The Rise of Bronze Age Society: Travels, Transmissions and Transformations|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2005}}</ref>{{page needed|date=October 2018}}{{refn|group=n|See [[Helen of Troy#Etymology|Etymology of Ἑλένη]].}} No unambiguous attestations of words for "sun" have been found yet, though the Mycenaean word for "sun" is reconstructed as *hāwélios.

